  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT252-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">talaimakaṉ varavaṟinta tōḻi “avar nammai valintu pōyiṉārkku em perumāṭṭi
          tīyaṉa kaṭantu (C2: kaṭintu) naṉku āṟṟiṉāy” eṉṟāṭkuk kiḻatti uraittatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Told by HER to the one who said “you have well had the
          strength as our great woman(?) chased away evil things(?) for him who was hard against us
          [and] went”, [i.e.] the confidante who knew about HIS coming. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT252">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l>neṭiya tiraṇṭa tōḷvaḷai nekiḻak</l>
          <l>koṭiya ṉākiya kuṉṟukeḻu nāṭaṉ</l>
          <l>varuvatōr kālai yiṉmukan tiriyātu</l>
          <l>kaṭavuṭ kaṟpi ṉavaṉetir pēṇi</l>
          <l>maṭavai maṉṟa nīyeṉak kaṭavupu</l>
          <l>tuṉiyal vāḻi tōḻi cāṉṟōr</l>
          <l>pukaḻu muṉṉar nāṇupa</l>
          <l>paḻiyāṅ kolpavō kāṇuṅ kālē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Don't be angry, oh friend,</l>
          <l rend="indent7">urging [me]</l>
          <l rend="indent3">“you [are] foolish indeed,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">being [all] esteem in front of him in [your] divine fidelity, <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">kaṭavuḷ kaṟpiṉ</term> : the connotations of this phrase are not at
            all clear. It could either be 1. "in divine fidelity", 2. "like the fidelity towards a
            god", 3. "as [according to] the teachings of god".</note></l>
          <l rend="indent3">[your] kind face not turned away in the morning from the one</l>
          <l rend="indent8">who is coming [back], <note place="foot">Or, with T.V.G., "[your] kind
            face unchanged in the morning, when he is coming".</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent3">the man from the hilly land, who has become cruel/faithless,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">so that the bangles come loose on [your] long, round upper arms.”</l>
          <l>Noble ones are ashamed who are praised in their presence; <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">muṉṉar</term> : literally "as such that are in front of
            [someone]".</note> </l>
          <l>how would blame be bearable to them</l>
          <l rend="indent6">while [one is actually] looking [at them] <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">kāṇum kālai</term> : this phrase could also be understood in a
            general sense ("when one considers it"), as such identical to an idiom that occurs
            frequently in the TP and probably having the purport that anybody considering it would
            come to the same conclusion.</note> ? <note place="foot">For the <term xml:lang="ta">
            cāṉṟōr </term> sentence one might also consider an application to the personal
            situation, which would mean taking <term xml:lang="ta">nāṇupa</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">kolpa</term> as honorific plurals along with varuvatōr: "Being in
            front [of me] he is ashamed when he is praised as noble; how could he bear blame while
            he is seen?" Srin. suggests a totally different alternative: "The noble ones who were
            praised by the ancients (<term xml:lang="ta">muṉṉar </term> in the temporal sense) would
            be ashamed (to act like that). How would blame be possible to them, if one considers
            it?"</note></l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
